The following Sophisms are not all susceptible of this solution. They are mostly material fallacias, arising from ainbiguity of language or falsity of assertion. But they are not treated of by Aris-totle as belonging to the Science of Logic, but to the Art of Dia- lectic‚ of which, as has been before observed, a considerable portion is material. In fact, Aristotle's Treatise περὶ σοφιστικῶν ἐλέγχων is merely an account of the pseudo-refutations prin- cipally in use among the Sophists of his day, whether depend- ing upon equivocal language, false assumption, or illogical reasoning. In relation to Logic, it has little more than a historic-al value. A strictly logical classificntion of fallacies should commence by distinguishii‘ig, in all the three operations of thought, between the matter which is given to, and the form which is given by the thinking act. Acts of conception, judg- ment, or reasoning which violate the laws of thought, and are therefore defective in form, should be classed as logical fal- lacies; those which are faulty in the conditions preliminary to the act of thought should be classed as material.
